Third Attempt - The 2016 US Elections

1. Project objective, Dataset, Tools and Libraries¶

1.1. Objective of the Project


Predict the winners of US presidential primaries in each of the US geographical units identified by Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) codes, typically (but not necessarily) a county. That is, based upon features encompassing demographical make-up and socio-economic status of the population in FIPS code area, we predict which candidate across both parties will score highest number of votes in that FIPS code area during the presidential primaries across both parties.

Two important facts about this data and project goals:

  1. At the US State level, except for a few swing states, it is remarkably easy to predict the winner of a political election. But for a more basic geographical unit, such as the one identified by FIPS code, voter's political opinion should be a little more challenging. Furthermore, to make things interesting, I have decided to predict the particular candidate of any party who will score highest votes in a county. That is to say, machine learning model will not only have to account for differences between the fans of Donald Trump and Bernie Sanders (very easy) but also between fans of Donald Trump and Ted Cruz (a little more challenging).

  2. A CAVEAT: More importantly, the two facts that, (1) in the early stages of presidential primaries, there are more candidates competing (specially in Republican primaries) than in the end, (2) the demographic features of States with late primaries can not account for dropped out primaries' candidates because samples are not arranged in time-series. (While we do engineer a new feature Date of Primaries by outsourcing information from Wikipedia to address this, it will still impose a limitation on the machine learning model, which may affect classification accuracy).

1.2 Tools and Libraries¶

We will use the well-known sklearn library to build, train and tune the models, in Python programming language. We will use pandas to manipulate the dataset, using dataframe application programming interface (API). We will also utilise some other common Python libraries, such as numpy. We will build the project in Jupyter notebook.

1.3 About the Dataset¶

This dataset was chosen to demonstrate working with raw data. It is not a part of any official Kaggle competition, but was contributed by members to the Kaggle and can be downloaded from Kaggle here. In its original form, dataset comprises of several files, many of them not related to the goals of this project. The files do not arrange feature and label columns properly, as we would have like them and we will do quite a bit of column computing, arranging, mixing and merging to get a dataset with which we can work.

We will download three files, the county_facts.csv, primary_results.csv and county_facts_dictionary.csv. The last file just provides names of columns of county_facts.csv, since they are quite long. The primary_results.csv file is in a format not very useful to us and we will manipulate to make it a column of county_facts.csv dataset.

2. Cleaning and Manipulation of Datasets¶

In its raw form, this set comprises of multiple files with required information scattered around. We will perform a series of steps for data cleansing and preparation steps.

2.1 Fixing NaN values¶

We start by checking the number of missing entries in the two datasets (third files provides list of columns). Here is the subset of county_facts dataframe which has NaN in any row.

In [0]:
county_facts_nan = county_facts[county_facts.isnull().any(axis=1)]

It can be easily inspected by printing out county_facts_nan that all the rows with missing values have missing value in column State. This is because, while most rows are reporting data for FIPS code areas, a few rows are for aggregates for States and US national data, and that is where area_name column suffices, so no State is listed (i.e., since this is not a result for FIPS code area, there is no need to say in which State this FIPS code area is located). This can be verified by counting rows of county_facts_nan and rows where State is missing, as done below:

In [0]:
print(len(county_facts_nan))
print(len(county_facts_nan.loc[county_facts_nan['state_abbreviation'].isnull()]))

52
52

The 50 NAN entries are for 50 US states, one NAN is for US national and one NAN is due to faulty data for second row of county_facts dataset where State is NAN, when it should be AL, for Alabama. We will fix that row and then drop the remaining 51 NAN rows because we are concenred with FIPS / county results, not states or national US results.

So we don't have FIPS code for New Hampshire. Luckily, the dataframe county_facts does list FIPS for New Hampshire. We can fill in the missing values for fips column in the result from corresponding values in the FIPS column in the county_facts. This is not as simple as it seems and is achieved in the following three cells.

In [0]:
# Fetch part of 'results' df where state is NH
NH_results = results.loc[results['state_abbreviation'] == 'NH']

# Fetch 'unique' counties in NH as listed in 'results' dataframe
NH_unique_counties = NH_results['county'].unique()

# Fetch NH counties listed in 'county_facts' dataframe (they are already unique)
NH_county = county_facts.loc[county_facts['state_abbreviation'] == 'NH']

Now we will fetch the FIPS code for each county and build a look-up dictionary.

In [0]:
NH_fips = []
for county in NH_unique_counties:
    # Since county name in 'county_facts' df is appended by word 'County', we fix county name 
    county_name = county + " County" 
    current = NH_county.loc[NH_county['area_name'] == county_name]
    NH_fips.append(int(current['fips']))

# Create lookup dictionary for NH county name and FIPS code
lookup = dict(zip(NH_unique_counties, NH_fips))

And finally, we will insert missing fips codes for New Hampshire counties into the results dataframe.

In [0]:
# Since all missing fips are in NH, no need to check for state
for c in NH_unique_counties:
    results.loc[results['county'] == c, 'fips'] = lookup[c]

Remember, we had kind of assumed all missing values were in FIPS column (as there were some hints suggesting it), so before proceeding to next step, let us be sure there are no missing values in results.

2.2 Fixing Data Type of fips Column in results Dataframe¶

FIPS is a code for a given county or area unit and should not be in float datatype. But a lot of the fips values are in float datatype (looking at the head of result above confirms this). We will convert them to int below.

In [0]:
results['fips'] = results['fips'].astype(int)

Turns out, no; we don't have results for all the FIPS in county_facts dataset, so we need to remove these rows from county_facts dataframe. This is accomplished below.

In [0]:
county_facts = county_facts[~county_facts['FIPS'].isin(missing_fips)]

# We need to redefine list of FIPS in county facts now, as county_facts has changed
fips_county_facts = county_facts['FIPS'].unique()

Now we will loop through unique FIPS in results, find the winner of each FIPS amongst all candidates from all the parties by counting the votes and we will create new column in county_facts where we insert the winner of the FIPS.

All of this is accomplished in following cell.

In [0]:
fips_winner = []

for f in fips_results:
    current = results[results['fips'] == f]
    max_votes = current['votes'].max()
    winner = current.loc[current['votes'] == max_votes]
    # In rare cases, two candidate have equal highest votes, 
    # so we just pick FIRST one as the winner 
    winner=winner.head(1)
    winner_candidate = winner['candidate'].item()
    fips_winner.append(winner_candidate)

winner_lookup = dict(zip(fips_results, fips_winner))

for f in fips_county_facts:
    county_facts.loc[county_facts['FIPS']==f,'Winner'] = winner_lookup[f]

4.1 Checking for Class Imbalance in Label¶

As noted earlier, this is a multi-class classification project and it is likely that there is class-imbalance in the dataset. Let us check the distribution of population in our label Winner:

In [0]:
def print_class_dist(vector):
    temp = pd.DataFrame(vector)
    temp.columns = ["Classes"]
    temp = pd.DataFrame(temp["Classes"].value_counts())
    temp.columns=["Counts"]
    percent_collector = []
    for idx in list(temp.index):
        percent_collector.append(str(round(temp["Counts"][idx]/len(vector)*100, 2))+"%")
    temp["Winner"] = percent_collector
    print(temp)

print_class_dist(train["Winner"])

4.3 Ranking Candidate Against Average Values of Features¶

So far, we have plotted general trends between selected features and each candidate winning. The focus was mostly distribution. It will be very interesting to see the average of feature values in counties (or FIPS code areas) where a candidate won. For example, in the subset of counties where a given candidate won, what is the average percentage of population with University degrees? We can plot bar graph for each candidate for each feature.

We write following two functions, where the the second function call the first one. The second function accepts four feature columns and calls the first function to compute average values for each feature and plots it as one of the subplots in 2-by-2 grid. The first function takes input as a feature column name. Inside the function it separates the FIPS areas won by each candidate and then finds average of the passed feature value in the respective counties. (While the approach used in the first function is not optimum in terms of computation resources, as it separates counties won by candidate every time it called but it is optimum in terms of memory resources, as multiple copies of dataframe will not need to be created.)

In [0]:
sns.set()
def average_where_won(feature):
    
    winner_feat_dict = {}
    
    for cand in winning_candidates:
        cand_won = train[train['Winner'] == cand]
        winner_feat_dict[cand] = cand_won[feature].mean()
        

    dict_ave = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(winner_feat_dict, orient = 'index')
    dict_ave.columns = ['Mean value']
    
    return dict_ave


def quad_plotter(features):

    sns.set(font_scale=1.3)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,12))
    colors=['red', 'blue', 'green', 'purple', '#624ea7', 'orange']
    for i in range(len(features)):
        average = average_where_won(features[i])
        plt.subplot(2, 2, i + 1)
        plt.bar(list(average.index), average['Mean value'], color=colors)
        plt.xticks(rotation=30)
        plt.gca().set_title(features[i])
        
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)
    plt.show()

As was shown at the beginning of this section, Senator Rubio won only 7 FIPS areas. 4.5 Taking Care of Class Imbalance¶

And finally, we will take care of class-imbalance:

In [0]:
from sklearn.utils import resample
import numpy as np

def LabelImbalanceRemover(data):
    
    majority_class   = data['Winner'].value_counts().index[0]
    minority_classes = list(set(np.unique(data['Winner'])) - set([majority_class]))
    
    data_temp = data[data['Winner'] == majority_class]
    majority_count = len(data_temp)
    print(majority_count)
    
    for label in minority_classes:
        current_class = data[data['Winner'] == label]
        temp = resample(current_class, replace=True, n_samples=int(majority_count*0.75), random_state=63)
        data_temp = pd.concat([data_temp, temp])
        
    data_temp.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    
    return data_temp

5.1 Bifurcation: Categorical and Non-categorical Subbranches of the Pipe¶

The following class, FeatureSelector will take the list of columns and return those columns. In our case, we will use this class to extract the numerical and categorical columns.

In [0]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin

class FeatureSelector(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    """
    The first section of pipeline extracts the the columns from dataset when list of columns is provided as argument.
    This will be used to extract either the numeric and categorical columns from total dataset, to process them individually.
    """
    def __init__(self, feature_names):
        self._feature_names = feature_names 
    
    #Return self nothing else to do here    
    def fit(self, X, y = None):
        return self 
    
    #Method that describes what we need this transformer to do
    def transform(self, X, y = None):
        return X[self._feature_names]

5.2 Handling Missing Values: `DataFrameImputer` will be used for both numerical and categorical columns ¶

The SimpleImputer built into the sklearn library support many strategies for handling missing value, with strategy='mean for numerical data and strategy='most_frequent for categorical. However, the implementation of strategy='most_frequent tends to be very slow, so we could use a trick wherein we pass strategy='common as strategy for categorical features and supply the most frequent entries of each column through the fill_values argument. However, since we have only one categorical column in this dataset, we will allow strategy='most_frequent without significant performance slow-down.

In [0]:
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer

class DataFrameImputer(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):

    """
    Just a wrapper for the SimpleImputer that keeps the dataframe structure
    """
    
    def __init__(self, strategy='mean'):
        self.strategy = strategy
        self.imp = None
        self.statistics_ = None

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        self.imp = SimpleImputer(strategy=self.strategy)
        self.imp.fit(X)
        self.statistics_ = pd.Series(self.imp.statistics_, index=X.columns)
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
        # X is supposed to be a DataFrame
        Ximp = self.imp.transform(X)
        Xfilled = pd.DataFrame(Ximp, index=X.index, columns=X.columns)
        return Xfilled

5.2. Processing Categorical Pipeline¶

5.2.1. Categorical Feature Engineering: ```Region``` and ```Date of Primary``` :¶

```Region```: Populations in various parts of US vote differently. While State of the particular FIPS code (county) will incorporate information about the region indireclty, making a separate feature will provide additional information for machine learning algorithm with which to work. The United States Census Bureau divides the nation into nine geographical regions, each comprising of several states. We will use these in this project.

```Date of Primary```: As mentioned in the introduction, in US presidential primaries, especially in the Republican primaries, candidates tend to drop out as the race progresses, so that only a few candidates remain by the end of primaries. This would obivously affect which candidate will win, since some candidates are not running and algorithms should be trained with this information. Since none of our independent variables reveal such information, we extract it from external sources; in particular, Wikipedia prodives these dates for Democrates and Republicans primaries. We will create a new column Date of Primaries, based upon when the primaries were held in the states, we assigned them a number; bigger the number, latter they had primaries.

The second problem that arises here is that in a few States, certainly not a majority of them, the Republican and Democratic parities had their primaries on different dates. Since Democratic candidates rarely drop out in the race and since there are few states where two parties have primaries on different dates, to keep things simple, we will just Republican primaries as date of primaries for states. This will introduce some minor inaccuracies for states but it will capture the trend well.

In the following cell, we create a class to create Region feature based upon these 9 geographical regions as well as use Wikipedia information to get presidential primaries dates for each state, create the dictionary with state and date paired up in it, and then engineer new feature Date of Primaries:

In [0]:
class CatFeatureEngineer(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):

    """
    In this section of pipeline, we will engineer two feature:
    -- 'Region'            : This will be engineered from feature 'State'
    -- 'Date of Primaries' : This will be engineered from data extracted from Wikipedia
    """

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self
    
    def region_creator(self, State):
        
        New_England        = ["Maine", "New Hampshire", "Vermont", "Massachusetts", "Rhode Island", "Connecticut"]
        Middle_Atlantic    = ["New York", "Pennsylvania", "New Jersey"]
        East_North_Central = ["Wisconsin", "Michigan", "Illinois", "Indiana", "Ohio"]
        West_North_Central = ["North Dakota", "South Dakota", "Nebraska", "Kansas", "Minnesota", "Iowa", "Missouri"]
        South_Atlantic     = ["Delaware", "Maryland", "DC", "Virginia", "West Virginia", "North Carolina", "South Carolina", "Georgia", "Florida"]
        East_South_Central = ["Kentucky", "Tennessee", "Mississippi", "Alabama"]
        West_South_Central = ["Oklahoma", "Texas", "Arkansas", "Louisiana"]
        Mountain           = ["Idaho", "Montana", "Wyoming", "Nevada", "Utah", "Colorado", "Arizona", "New Mexico"]
        Pacific             = ["Alaska", "Washington", "Oregon", "California", "Hawaii"]
        
        if State in New_England:
            return "New England"
        elif State in Middle_Atlantic:
            return "Middle Atlantic"
        elif State in East_North_Central:
            return "East North Central"
        elif State in West_North_Central:
            return "West North Central" 
        elif State in South_Atlantic:
            return "South Atlantic"
        elif State in East_South_Central:
            return "East South Central"
        elif State in West_South_Central:
            return "West South Central"
        elif State in Mountain:
            return "Mountain"
        elif State in Pacific:
            return "Pacific"
        else:
            return "Notfound"
        
        
    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        
        X["Region"] = X["State"].apply(self.region_creator)
        
        dictRepub = {"Iowa" : "February 1", "New Hampshire" : "February 9", "South Carolina" : "February 20", 
                     "Nevada" : "February 23", "Alabama" : "March 1", "Alaska"  : "March 5", "Arkansas" : "March 5",
                     "Colorado" : "March 5", "Georgia" : "March 5", "Massachusetts" : "March 5", "Minnesota" : "March 5",

5.2.4. Categorical Columns: One-Hot Encoding¶

The dummy encoding is required since some machine learning algorithms cannot work with non-numeric variables. In the following we create a class to carry out dummay encoding.

In [0]:
class dummify(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):

    """
    Wrapper for get dummies
    """
    
    def __init__(self, drop_first=False, match_cols=True):
        self.drop_first = drop_first
        self.columns = []  # useful to well behave with FeatureUnion
        self.match_cols = match_cols

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        self.columns = []  # for safety, when we refit we want new columns
        return self
    
    def match_columns(self, X):
        miss_train = list(set(X.columns) - set(self.columns))
        miss_test = list(set(self.columns) - set(X.columns))
        
        err = 0
        
        if len(miss_test) > 0:
            for col in miss_test:
                X[col] = 0  # insert a column for the missing dummy
                err += 1
        if len(miss_train) > 0:
            for col in miss_train:
                del X[col]  # delete the column of the extra dummy
                err += 1

        X = X[self.columns]
        return X
        
    def transform(self, X):
        X = pd.get_dummies(X, drop_first=self.drop_first)
        if (len(self.columns) > 0): 
            if self.match_cols:
                X = self.match_columns(X)
            self.columns = X.columns
        else:
            self.columns = X.columns
        return X
    
    def get_features_name(self):
        return self.columns

5.3. Processing Numerical Pipeline¶

In [0]:
class SkewRemover(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    """
    ABC
    """

    def __init__(self, cols_with_negative_values):
        self.columns = []  # useful to well behave with FeatureUnion
        self.cols_with_negative_values = cols_with_negative_values
        

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self
    
    def adjust_negative(self, X, column):
        X[column] = X[column] + (-1*(np.min(X[column] - 1)))
        return X

    def remove_skew(self, X, column):
        X[column] = np.log1p(X[column])
        return X

    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        for col in X.columns:
            if col in self.cols_with_negative_values:
                X = self.adjust_negative(X, col)

            X = self.remove_skew(X, col)
        
        self.columns = X.columns 
        return X
    
    def get_features_name(self):
        return self.columns

In [0]:
from sklearn.pipeline import FeatureUnion

class FeatureUnion_df(TransformerMixin, BaseEstimator):
    '''
    Wrapper of FeatureUnion but returning a Dataframe, 
    the column order follows the concatenation done by FeatureUnion

    transformer_list: list of Pipelines

    '''
    def __init__(self, transformer_list, n_jobs=None, transformer_weights=None, verbose=False):
        self.transformer_list = transformer_list
        self.n_jobs = n_jobs
        self.transformer_weights = transformer_weights
        self.verbose = verbose  # these are necessary to work inside of GridSearch or similar
        self.feat_un = FeatureUnion(self.transformer_list, 
                                    self.n_jobs, 
                                    self.transformer_weights, 
                                    self.verbose)
        
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        self.feat_un.fit(X)
        return self

    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        
        X_tr = self.feat_un.transform(X)
        columns = []
        
        for trsnf in self.transformer_list:
            cols = trsnf[1].steps[-1][1].get_features_name()  # getting the features name from the last step of each pipeline
            columns += list(cols)

        X_tr = pd.DataFrame(X_tr, index=X.index, columns=columns)

        return X_tr

    def get_params(self, deep=True):  # necessary to well behave in GridSearch
        return self.feat_un.get_params(deep=deep)

5.5. Standardisation of the Features¶

In [0]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, RobustScaler

class StandardiseDF(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    '''
    Wrapper of StandardScaler or RobustScaler
    '''
    def __init__(self, method='standard'):
        self.scl = None
        self.scale_ = None
        self.method = method
        if self.method == 'sdandard':
            self.mean_ = None
        elif method == 'robust':
            self.center_ = None
        self.columns = None  # this is useful when it is the last step of a pipeline before the model

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        if self.method == 'standard':
            self.scl = StandardScaler()
            self.scl.fit(X)
            self.mean_ = pd.Series(self.scl.mean_, index=X.columns)
        elif self.method == 'robust':
            self.scl = RobustScaler()
            self.scl.fit(X)
            self.center_ = pd.Series(self.scl.center_, index=X.columns)
        self.scale_ = pd.Series(self.scl.scale_, index=X.columns)
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
        # assumes X is a DataFrame
        Xscl = self.scl.transform(X)
        Xscaled = pd.DataFrame(Xscl, index=X.index, columns=X.columns)
        self.columns = X.columns
        return Xscaled

    def get_feature_names(self):
        return list(self.columns)  # this is going to be useful when coupled with FeatureUnion

5.5. Dimentionality Reduction¶

In [0]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

class CustomPCA(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    '''
    Wrapper of StandardScaler or RobustScaler
    '''
    def __init__(self, preserve_variance=0.95):
        self.preserve_variance = preserve_variance


    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        self.pipe_pca = PCA(self.preserve_variance)
        self.pipe_pca.fit(X)
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
        X_tr = self.pipe_pca.transform(X)
        cols = ['principal component number ' + str(num) for num in range(1, X_tr.shape[1] + 1)]
        X_tr = pd.DataFrame(X_tr, columns=cols)
        return X_tr

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc
from sklearn.preprocessing import label_binarize
from scipy import interp
from itertools import cycle


def custom_roc_auc(y_test_bin, y_score, n_classes):
    
    fpr, tpr, roc_auc = dict(), dict(), dict()
    
    for i in range(n_classes):
        fpr[i], tpr[i], _ = roc_curve(y_test_bin[:, i], y_score[:, i])

        roc_auc[i] = auc(fpr[i], tpr[i])
        
    fpr["micro"], tpr["micro"], _ = roc_curve(y_test_bin.ravel(), y_score.ravel())
    roc_auc["micro"] = auc(fpr["micro"], tpr["micro"])

    all_fpr = np.unique(np.concatenate([fpr[i] for i in range(n_classes)]))
    
    mean_tpr = np.zeros_like(all_fpr)

    for i in range(n_classes):
        mean_tpr += interp(all_fpr, fpr[i], tpr[i])
    
    mean_tpr /= n_classes
    
    fpr["macro"] = all_fpr
    tpr["macro"] = mean_tpr
    roc_auc["macro"] = auc(fpr["macro"], tpr["macro"])

    return roc_auc['macro']

We have successfully taken care of class-imbalance.
